  <!-- SEOUL USEFUL INFORMATION -->
  <section id="seoul-info" class="home-section">
    <div class="home-container">
      <h2 class="home-section-title scroll-animate">Seoul Useful Information</h2>

      <div class="home-info-grid">
        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Seoul at a Glance</h3>
          <p>Seoul, the capital of South Korea, is recognized as a leading global city characterized by a thriving economy and a high quality of life. It serves as a significant hub for technology, electronics, design, and business. The city seamlessly blends ancient traditions with modern advancements, showcasing skyscrapers alongside historic palaces and pagodas. Despite its large size, Seoul offers efficient public transportation and accessible dining options.</p>
          <ul class="home-list">
            <li><strong>Dialling code:</strong> +82</li>
            <li><strong>Currency:</strong> Korean Won (KRW)</li>
            <li><strong>Weather (September):</strong> 15–25°C, occasional rain, autumn</li>
            <li><strong>Time Zone:</strong> GMT +9 (no daylight saving)</li>
            <li><strong>Incheon International Airport (ICN) to The Westin Seoul Parnas:</strong> approx. 1 hr 15 mins</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.05">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Weather &amp; Packing</h3>
          <p>Weather in September: average high 25°C, average low 15°C. Pack light jackets and sweaters for layering as the weather can be chilly in the morning and at night, comfortable shoes and body lotions to keep moisturised.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.1">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Currency &amp; Money</h3>
          <p>The South Korean won (₩ / KRW) is the official currency used throughout Seoul. Seoul is very card-friendly, but it is advisable to carry some cash for markets and street food. ATMs are readily available but typically charge a withdrawal fee of approximately ₩3,000–₩5,000 per transaction. Currency exchange services and ATMs can be found at the airport and major shopping malls.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.15">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Power Plugs &amp; Sockets</h3>
          <p>In South Korea, power plugs and sockets (outlets) of type C and type F are used. The standard voltage is 220V at a frequency of 60Hz. A universal travel adapter is recommended for convenience.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card home-info-card--wide scroll-animate">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Seoul Transportation to City</h3>
          <p>Seoul's transportation system is designed to be user-friendly and efficient, making it easy for visitors to navigate the city.</p>
          <ul class="home-list">
            <li><strong>Subway:</strong> Extensive network, operates 24/7, reliable for city travel.</li>
            <li><strong>Bus:</strong> Color-coded buses covering major hotels and districts. T-money card used for boarding.</li>
            <li><strong>Taxi:</strong> Available 24/7, ideal for luggage or late-night travel.</li>
            <li><strong>KTX:</strong> For long-distance travel between cities in Korea.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>Use a T-Money transit card for easy transfers. Navigation apps like Naver Map or KakaoMap are recommended.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.05">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Useful Apps</h3>
          <ul class="home-list">
            <li><strong>Naver Map:</strong> More tourist-friendly than Google Maps in Korea. Kakao Map is also available.</li>
            <li><strong>Papago:</strong> Smart AI translations for conversational use.</li>
            <li><strong>K-Ride or Uber:</strong> Compare both apps for better rates and car selection.</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.1">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Korean Emergency Hotlines</h3>
          <ul class="home-list">
            <li><strong>112</strong> – Police</li>
            <li><strong>119</strong> – Fire &amp; Ambulance</li>
            <li><strong>182</strong> – Missing Persons &amp; Stolen Vehicles</li>
            <li><strong>1339</strong> – Korea Center for Disease Control (KCDC) Foreigner Helpline</li>
            <li><strong>1330</strong> – Korea Tourism Organization's Travel Helpline</li>
            <li><strong>1345</strong> – Immigration</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="home-info-card scroll-animate" data-delay="0.15">
          <h3 class="home-subheading">Safety &amp; Security</h3>
          <ul class="home-list">
            <li>Follow general safety precautions</li>
            <li>Have a copy of travel document/ID when moving about (hard copy or copy in phone)</li>
            <li>Global Security will be on-site at all times during the event</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
